<font color="#FF0000">THE HERO WARRIOR AND PTSD</font><br>
<tt>Fri Oct  3 12:38:28 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
TOM;<br>
I feel much like what you have stated. I don't believe I suffer from PTSD, I believe I experienced and dealt with it in Nam and left it buried there in the mud, in the rice paddies fields and in the jungles of Southeast Asia. Vietnam prepared us for independance and for seeking what is right. The Vietnam vets may also be about the only ones still holding onto some faith in justice and in America.<br><br>
TO SW and ED<br>
Yes, I believe God did spare me for a reason, and I have enjoyed life to its fullest. Even in the Police Department I was often referred to as an officer that did not get excited or that anything bothered. I believe that inner peace was accomplished one particular day in Vietnam and then on the hills over looking the City of Los Angeles when I finally submitted to God.<br><br>
TO ALL, <br>
I have not had to deal with PTSD, but there has always been a deep need within for closure, which I feel is not a related to PTSD but needful for all of us to experience.  Our reunion this year closed a lot of holes and fulfilled a deep need that can only be understood by those we shared experiences with.<br><br>
Was the need for closure because I felt the job was left undone? Was it because of the rejection from our countrymen following our return? Or was it because of what I learned in Nam, to trust someone else with my life, because of those moments of laughter, joy, peace, love, as well as fear which are all those things that bind and made us all into a unit, that was nowhere else to be found afterwards? Was it validation of what we accomplished together?<br><br>
THE HORROR OF WAR<br>
Soldiers, individuals that have gone to war have for years encountered the horrors of war but those things have not bother me, they do not hunt me. Many before us saw the same or more, but never were they insulted upon their return as we were and those are scares that cannot be repaired as Art mentioned in tread #111, it is &quot;impossible in some cases, to dismiss the destructive words of extraordinarily ignorant people.&quot;<br>
. <br><br>
Today people continue to advocate that healing can only come by acknowledging that our involvement in Vietnam meaningless. Nothing can be further from the truth, evidence of this can be found here, in some of these treads where some have succumbed to these tiny bits of morsels to appease their hunger in search for closure, but their soul has found no rest. <br><br>
THE HERO WARRIOR<br>
I believe a lot has to do with the over all duty we performed. We believed in our country and it was not selfish nor unusual to expect recognition for our righteous and justifiable service to our country. The hero warrior,  the conquering warrior has always been celebrated upon his return home. The hero warrior has always been recognized by the medals he won and the spoils of war he obtained. He has represented honor, and glory. Has always been looked upon as a savior, a lover, represented individual courage and collective brotherhood in the face of danger. We were denied those rights of passage and as a result not only did the Vietnam veteran suffer but so did his loved ones and in the end the shadow of shame has continued to prevail over our nation.<br><br>
Not only were our deeds debased, we were denied the right to share those precious memories and powerful experiences with others including our loved ones. That closure that remains unfulfilled. No one to talk to, to share our story with, to communicate with about what we saw, shared and felt.  We expected a welcome home the conquering hero as our predecessors had experienced before us, instead we were subjected to ridicule, insults and were sped upon. Why? Was it something we did wrong in that war? NO, it was pure misinformation and disinformation propagated against us at home and that was a war we had not prepared to fight. Even Motel 6 turned out the light and closed the window. <br>

<p><code>-- Cookbarela@iname.com  (Cook Barela) </code><p>


